1 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3500.3 of Title 56, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 As used in the Streamlined Services Act:
5 1. "Applicant" means any individual or household seeking
6 benefits or services through the programs specified in Section 2 of
7 this act; and
8 2. "Integrated access system" means a single, technology-driven
9 platform that enables residents to apply for, manage, and renew
10 benefits across multiple human services programs.
11 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
12 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3500.4 of Title 56, unless there
13 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
14 The Department of Human Services shall develop, implement, and
15 administer an integrated access system that:
16 1. Provides a single point of access for applicants to apply
17 for and manage benefits across eligible programs;
18 2. Utilizes a secure, user-friendly, web-based platform
19 accessible via computers, mobile devices, and kiosks;
20 3. Includes functionality for real-time status updates,
21 document uploads, and communication between applicants and
22 administrative staff;
23 4. Ensures accessibility for individuals with disabilities and
24 individuals with limited English proficiency; and
Req. No. 11383 Page 3

1 5. Integrates data-sharing capabilities to streamline
2 eligibility determinations while maintaining compliance with state
3 and federal privacy laws.
4 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3500.5 of Title 56, unless there
6 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 A. The Department of Human Services shall:
8 1. Issue a request for proposals (RFP) for the development and
9 implementation of the integrated access system within six (6) months
10 of the effective date of this act; and
11 2. Launch the system for public use within one (1) year of the
12 effective date of this act.
13 B. The Department shall establish interim benchmarks and
14 provide progress updates to the Governor and the Legislature every
15 six (6) months until the system is fully operational.
16 SECTION 6. This act shall become effective July 1, 2025.
17 SECTION 7. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
18 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
19 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
20 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
